"# Chapter 3: Easing

A button descends when you press it. A door swings shut. A bird alights on a branch. Each of these motions has a *shape* — not the path through space (we'll drill that in Chapter 4), but the shape of the *move itself* over time. Does it start slowly and build speed? Does it coast in and brake hard at the end? Does it move at a steady clip from first frame to last?

The difference between a move that *eases* and one that doesn't is the difference between something that feels alive and something that feels mechanical. Linear motion — constant velocity, like we explored in Chapter 2 — is the exception in the natural world, not the rule. Everything with weight accelerates into a move and decelerates out of it. Everything with intention hesitates, then commits. Easing is how we give the sprite's world that quality of *aliveness*.

This chapter drills the **:easing** axis of the motion 5-tuple. We'll start with the starkest contrast — linear vs eased — and climb toward layered easings, custom curves, and the feel of a move that *settles* rather than merely stopping.

[VISUAL: Three circles traveling the same horizontal distance — one moving linearly (evenly spaced frames), one easing in (tight spacing at start, wide at end), one easing out (wide spacing at start, tight at end).]

---

## The Linear Baseline

Before we can feel easing, we need to see what it replaces. Here's a box moving from left to right over 60 frames at constant velocity — no acceleration, no deceleration, just uniform motion:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (entity/set-vel! box 4 0)
  (world/step 60))
```

It moves. It gets there. But it doesn't *feel* like it decided to go or chose to stop — it's a mechanism, not a gesture.

---

## Ease-Out: The Arrival

Now the same move, but with an ease-out. The box starts fast and slows as it approaches its destination, like a hand reaching for a cup and decelerating as it arrives:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (entity/glide! box 290 300 :frames 60 :ease 'out))
```

`entity/glide!` is our first motion verb that bakes easing into the move. The `:ease 'out` parameter says \"start at full speed, slow to rest.\" The *distance* covered and the *duration* are the same as the linear move, but the *feel* is completely different.

---

## Ease-In: The Departure

Ease-in is the mirror: the box starts slowly and builds speed, like gathering courage before a leap:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (entity/glide! box 290 300 :frames 60 :ease 'in))
```

Ease-in moves feel *decisive* — the entity commits to the move and accelerates into it. They're less common than ease-out in UI (where you want arrivals to feel gentle) but crucial for departures, launches, and anything that reads as *effort*.

---

## Ease-In-Out: The Full Arc

Combine them: start slow, accelerate to midpoint, decelerate to rest. This is the shape of most natural motion — a full breath, in and out:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (entity/glide! box 290 300 :frames 60 :ease 'in-out))
```

Ease-in-out is the workhorse easing. It feels organic, intentional, and complete. When in doubt, reach for `'in-out`.

---

## Side-by-Side Comparison

Let's see all four shapes at once — linear, ease-in, ease-out, ease-in-out — so the difference is unmistakable:

```scheme
(let ((linear (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 200 :color 'gray))
      (ease-in (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 250 :color 'blue))
      (ease-out (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300 :color 'green))
      (in-out (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 350 :color 'purple)))
  (entity/set-vel! linear 4 0)
  (entity/glide! ease-in 290 250 :frames 60 :ease 'in)
  (entity/glide! ease-out 290 300 :frames 60 :ease 'out)
  (entity/glide! in-out 290 350 :frames 60 :ease 'in-out)
  (world/step 60))
```

Watch how the blue box (ease-in) lags behind at the start but catches up. The green box (ease-out) leads early but slows. The purple box (in-out) does both. The gray box just *goes*.

---

## Vertical Motion: A Falling Leaf

Easing isn't just for horizontal slides. Here's a leaf drifting down with ease-in-out, giving it a gentle, settling quality:

```scheme
(let ((leaf (world/spawn 'leaf :x 400 :y 100)))
  (entity/glide! leaf 400 500 :frames 90 :ease 'in-out))
```

The same easing applied to a vertical move reads as *drift* rather than *slide* — context matters.

---

## Duration and Feel

The *length* of an eased move changes its emotional weight. Here's the same ease-out move at three durations — 30 frames (brisk), 60 frames (comfortable), 120 frames (languid):

```scheme
(let ((fast (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 200 :color 'red))
      (medium (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 250 :color 'yellow))
      (slow (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300 :color 'blue)))
  (entity/glide! fast 290 200 :frames 30 :ease 'out)
  (entity/glide! medium 290 250 :frames 60 :ease 'out)
  (entity/glide! slow 290 300 :frames 120 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 120))
```

Fast ease-out feels *snappy*. Slow ease-out feels *luxurious*. The easing curve is the same; the tempo changes everything.

---

## Ease Power: Subtle vs Aggressive

Some easing verbs let you dial the *strength* of the ease — how aggressively it accelerates or decelerates. A gentle ease-out coasts in smoothly; an aggressive ease-out *brakes hard*:

```scheme
(let ((gentle (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 250 :color 'green))
      (strong (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300 :color 'red)))
  (entity/glide! gentle 290 250 :frames 60 :ease 'out :power 2)
  (entity/glide! strong 290 300 :frames 60 :ease 'out :power 4)
  (world/step 60))
```

`:power 2` is the default — a quadratic ease, gentle and familiar. `:power 4` is quartic — more extreme, more *feeling*. Use higher powers when you want the easing to be *obvious*, when subtlety would be lost.

---

## Elastic Ease: Overshoot and Settle

Some easings don't just decelerate — they *overshoot* the target and spring back, like a rubber band snapping into place:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (entity/glide! box 290 300 :frames 80 :ease 'elastic-out))
```

`'elastic-out` gives the move a playful, bouncy quality. It's too much for most UI, but perfect for anything that should feel *springy* — a notification appearing, a character bouncing to a stop, a UI element with personality.

---

## Back Ease: Anticipation Before Departure

A back-ease pulls *away* from the target before moving toward it — like winding up before a throw:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 150 :y 300)))
  (entity/glide! box 350 300 :frames 60 :ease 'back-out))
```

The box briefly moves *left* (away from the destination) before gliding right and settling. This is *anticipation* — one of Disney's 12 principles — baked into an easing curve.

---

## Bounce Ease: Settling After Impact

A bounce ease simulates the box hitting the ground and settling through a series of diminishing bounces:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 200 :y 100)))
  (entity/glide! box 200 400 :frames 80 :ease 'bounce-out))
```

It's a shorthand for a physically plausible settle — useful when you want the *feel* of bounce without simulating the physics.

---

## Combining Horizontal and Vertical Easing

Easing each axis independently gives you compound motion with different arrival feels. Here, a box glides diagonally with ease-out on X but ease-in on Y:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 100)))
  (entity/glide! box 350 400 :frames 80 :ease-x 'out :ease-y 'in))
```

The horizontal motion slows to rest; the vertical motion accelerates downward. The result reads as a *toss* that's losing horizontal momentum but falling under gravity — even though we haven't invoked `world/gravity!` yet.

---

## Easing a Color Fade

Easing isn't limited to position. Here's a box fading from opaque to transparent with ease-out, so the fade *slows* as it reaches invisibility:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 200 :y 300 :alpha 1.0)))
  (entity/set! box 'alpha-target 0.0)
  (entity/set! box 'alpha-frames 80)
  (entity/set! box 'alpha-ease 'out)
  (world/step 80))
```

<!-- BUILD: entity-level alpha tweening may need interpolator wiring; placeholder for chapter continuity -->
*[needs: entity alpha interpolation]*

The *same easing curve* applied to opacity instead of position. Easing is a *shape over time*, not a verb tied to a specific property.

---

## Easing a Rotation

A box spinning to face a new direction, easing in-out so it starts and ends gently:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 200 :y 300 :angle 0)))
  (entity/set! box 'angle-target (* PI 0.5))
  (entity/set! box 'angle-frames 60)
  (entity/set! box 'angle-ease 'in-out)
  (world/step 60))
```

<!-- BUILD: entity-level angle tweening placeholder -->
*[needs: entity angle interpolation]*

Same principle, different axis. Easing is *universal*.

---

## Staggered Arrivals: Easing + Offset

Three boxes gliding to the same destination, each starting a few frames after the last. They arrive in sequence, not all at once:

```scheme
(let ((box1 (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 200))
      (box2 (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 250))
      (box3 (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (entity/glide! box1 350 200 :frames 60 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 10)
  (entity/glide! box2 350 250 :frames 60 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 10)
  (entity/glide! box3 350 300 :frames 60 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 60))
```

The 10-frame offsets create a *cascade*. Same easing, different timing. This is the embryo of *choreography*.

---

## Custom Easing via Interpolation Factor

For complete control, you can define your own easing function. Here's a box moving with a hand-rolled ease-out curve, computed frame-by-frame:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300))
      (start-x 50)
      (end-x 350)
      (frames 60))
  (letrec ((ease-out (lambda (t) (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
           (step (lambda (frame)
                   (when (< frame frames)
                     (let* ((t (/ frame frames))
                            (eased-t (ease-out t))
                            (x (+ start-x (* (- end-x start-x) eased-t))))
                       (entity/set-pos! box x 300)
                       (world/step 1)
                       (step (+ frame 1)))))))
    (step 0)))
```

The `ease-out` lambda is a quadratic ease function: `1 - (1 - t)²`. We compute the interpolation factor `t`, ease it, then use the eased value to position the box. This pattern — interpolate, ease, apply — is the skeleton of every tweening system.

---

## Easing with a Sine Wave

A sine-based ease gives a smooth, organic feel. Here's a box moving with a sine-out curve:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300))
      (start-x 50)
      (end-x 350)
      (frames 60))
  (letrec ((ease-sine-out (lambda (t) (dsin (* t PI 0.5))))
           (step (lambda (frame)
                   (when (< frame frames)
                     (let* ((t (/ frame frames))
                            (eased-t (ease-sine-out t))
                            (x (+ start-x (* (- end-x start-x) eased-t))))
                       (entity/set-pos! box x 300)
                       (world/step 1)
                       (step (+ frame 1)))))))
    (step 0)))
```

The sine curve (first quarter of the wave) produces an ease that feels very *natural* — it's the shape of a pendulum slowing as it reaches the top of its swing.

---

## Easing with an Exponential Curve

An exponential ease decelerates *hard* near the end — useful for something that's *fighting* to stop:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300))
      (start-x 50)
      (end-x 350)
      (frames 60))
  (letrec ((ease-expo-out (lambda (t) (- 1 (dpow 2 (* -10 t)))))
           (step (lambda (frame)
                   (when (< frame frames)
                     (let* ((t (/ frame frames))
                            (eased-t (ease-expo-out t))
                            (x (+ start-x (* (- end-x start-x) eased-t))))
                       (entity/set-pos! box x 300)
                       (world/step 1)
                       (step (+ frame 1)))))))
    (step 0)))
```

Exponential eases feel *abrupt* — they cover most of the distance quickly, then slow dramatically. Use them for impacts, sudden stops, or moves that should feel *forceful*.

---

## Mirrored Ease-In from Ease-Out

Any ease-out curve can become an ease-in by inverting the timeline: `eased_in(t) = 1 - eased_out(1 - t)`. Here's that transformation:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300))
      (start-x 50)
      (end-x 350)
      (frames 60))
  (letrec ((ease-out (lambda (t) (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
           (ease-in (lambda (t) (- 1 (ease-out (- 1 t)))))
           (step (lambda (frame)
                   (when (< frame frames)
                     (let* ((t (/ frame frames))
                            (eased-t (ease-in t))
                            (x (+ start-x (* (- end-x start-x) eased-t))))
                       (entity/set-pos! box x 300)
                       (world/step 1)
                       (step (+ frame 1)))))))
    (step 0)))
```

This is the mathematical relationship between in and out. Understanding it gives you the entire easing family from a single curve.

---

## Building Ease-In-Out from Ease-In and Ease-Out

Combine ease-in for the first half and ease-out for the second half:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300))
      (start-x 50)
      (end-x 350)
      (frames 60))
  (letrec ((ease-out (lambda (t) (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
           (ease-in (lambda (t) (- 1 (ease-out (- 1 t)))))
           (ease-in-out (lambda (t)
                          (if (< t 0.5)
                              (* 0.5 (ease-in (* 2 t)))
                              (+ 0.5 (* 0.5 (ease-out (- (* 2 t) 1)))))))
           (step (lambda (frame)
                   (when (< frame frames)
                     (let* ((t (/ frame frames))
                            (eased-t (ease-in-out t))
                            (x (+ start-x (* (- end-x start-x) eased-t))))
                       (entity/set-pos! box x 300)
                       (world/step 1)
                       (step (+ frame 1)))))))
    (step 0)))
```

The first half runs ease-in at double speed; the second half runs ease-out at double speed. Scaled and stitched. This is how all compound easings are built.

---

## Easing a Series of Moves

A box that makes three moves in sequence, each with its own easing:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (entity/glide! box 200 300 :frames 40 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 40)
  (entity/glide! box 200 150 :frames 30 :ease 'in-out)
  (world/step 30)
  (entity/glide! box 350 150 :frames 50 :ease 'in)
  (world/step 50))
```

Each leg has its own duration and easing. The pauses between moves (the `world/step` calls) are part of the *timing* — we'll drill that in Chapter 5, but notice how easing and timing are *separate* concerns. You can vary one without touching the other.

---

## Easing Multiple Entities in Formation

Three boxes gliding in parallel, each with a different easing, so the formation *morphs* as it moves:

```scheme
(let ((linear-box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 200))
      (ease-box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 250))
      (bounce-box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (entity/set-vel! linear-box 4 0)
  (entity/glide! ease-box 290 250 :frames 60 :ease 'in-out)
  (entity/glide! bounce-box 290 300 :frames 60 :ease 'bounce-out)
  (world/step 60))
```

The formation starts aligned and distorts as each box follows its own easing curve. When they arrive, the formation is aligned again — but the *journey* was different for each.

---

## Easing Toward a Moving Target

A box easing toward a target that's also moving. The glide destination is computed at the start, so the box doesn't track the target — it eases toward where the target *was*:

```scheme
(let ((target (world/spawn 'target :x 300 :y 300 :color 'red))
      (chaser (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300 :color 'blue)))
  (entity/set-vel! target 2 0)
  (let ((target-x (entity/x target))
        (target-y (entity/y target)))
    (entity/glide! chaser target-x target-y :frames 60 :ease 'out))
  (world/step 60))
```

The chaser eases smoothly, but the target keeps moving — the chaser arrives at where the target *used to be*. This is the difference between easing toward a *position* and easing toward an *entity* (which requires re-computing the destination every frame — we'll drill that in later chapters).

---

## Easing Toward a Computed Position

A box easing toward the midpoint between two other boxes:

```scheme
(let ((anchor1 (world/spawn 'anchor :x 100 :y 200 :color 'gray))
      (anchor2 (world/spawn 'anchor :x 400 :y 400 :color 'gray))
      (box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 100 :color 'blue)))
  (let ((mid-x (/ (+ (entity/x anchor1) (entity/x anchor2)) 2))
        (mid-y (/ (+ (entity/y anchor1) (entity/y anchor2)) 2)))
    (entity/glide! box mid-x mid-y :frames 60 :ease 'in-out)
    (world/step 60)))
```

The midpoint is computed once, then used as the glide target. The box eases toward that computed position — smoothly, organically.

---

## Easing Along a Path (Two-Leg Approximation)

A box that eases along a two-segment path — first to a waypoint, then to the final destination:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (entity/glide! box 250 150 :frames 40 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 40)
  (entity/glide! box 450 300 :frames 40 :ease 'in)
  (world/step 40))
```

Each leg is eased independently. The path has a *corner* — the box decelerates into the waypoint, then accelerates out of it. This is the seed of path-following with ease-in/out at each control point.

---

## Easing With a Hold at the Midpoint

A box eases to a midpoint, *holds* there for a beat, then eases to the final destination:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (entity/glide! box 250 300 :frames 30 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 30)
  (world/step 20)
  (entity/glide! box 450 300 :frames 30 :ease 'in)
  (world/step 30))
```

The 20-frame hold is *stillness* between two moves. This is *timing* — the pause is as important as the motion. Easing gives shape to each move; timing gives rhythm to the sequence.

---

## Easing with Anticipation and Follow-Through

A box pulls back (anticipation), then glides forward (the main move), then drifts a bit past and settles (follow-through):

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 200 :y 300)))
  (entity/glide! box 150 300 :frames 15 :ease 'in)
  (world/step 15)
  (entity/glide! box 400 300 :frames 40 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 40)
  (entity/glide! box 420 300 :frames 20 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 20))
```

Three moves: back, forward, settle. Each eased to feel continuous. This is Disney's anticipation and follow-through built from eased glides.

---

## Easing a Bounce to Rest (Manual Decay)

A box bouncing horizontally, each bounce covering half the distance of the last, with ease-in-out on each arc:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (letrec ((bounce (lambda (x dist count)
                     (when (> count 0)
                       (entity/glide! box (+ x dist) 300 :frames 20 :ease 'in-out)
                       (world/step 20)
                       (bounce (+ x dist) (* dist -0.5) (- count 1))))))
    (bounce 50 200 5)))
```

Each bounce is an eased move; the distance decays exponentially. The result reads as a ball rolling to rest.

---

## Easing a Vertical Bounce to Rest

Same idea, but vertical — a ball bouncing on the ground, each bounce eased and half the height of the last:

```scheme
(let ((ball (world/spawn 'ball :x 200 :y 100)))
  (letrec ((bounce (lambda (y height count)
                     (when (> count 0)
                       (entity/glide! ball 200 400 :frames 15 :ease 'in)
                       (world/step 15)
                       (entity/glide! ball 200 (- 400 height) :frames 15 :ease 'out)
                       (world/step 15)
                       (bounce (- 400 height) (* height 0.5) (- count 1))))))
    (bounce 100 200 4)))
```

Fall (ease-in), rise (ease-out), decay. This is a physically plausible bounce built from easing primitives.

---

## Easing a Pendulum Swing (Sine Oscillation with Decay)

A box swaying back and forth, each swing smaller than the last, like a pendulum coming to rest:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 200 :y 200))
      (center-x 200)
      (amplitude 100))
  (letrec ((swing (lambda (frame max-frames)
                    (when (< frame max-frames)
                      (let* ((t (/ frame max-frames))
                             (decay (- 1 t))
                             (offset (* amplitude decay (dsin (* t TAU 2)))))
                        (entity/set-pos! box (+ center-x offset) 200)
                        (world/step 1)
                        (swing (+ frame 1) max-frames))))))
    (swing 0 120)))
```

The sine wave provides the oscillation; the `(- 1 t)` decay shrinks the amplitude. No easing *function* here — the sine wave *is* the easing. But the principle is the same: a value that changes smoothly over time.

---

## Easing a Spiral Inward

A box spiraling toward a center point, the radius shrinking with ease-out:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 400 :y 300))
      (center-x 300)
      (center-y 300)
      (start-radius 150))
  (letrec ((spiral (lambda (frame max-frames)
                     (when (< frame max-frames)
                       (let* ((t (/ frame max-frames))
                              (eased-t (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
                              (radius (* start-radius (- 1 eased-t)))
                              (angle (* t TAU 3))
                              (x (+ center-x (* radius (dcos angle))))
                              (y (+ center-y (* radius (dsin angle)))))
                         (entity/set-pos! box x y)
                         (world/step 1)
                         (spiral (+ frame 1) max-frames))))))
    (spiral 0 120)))
```

The radius shrinks with quadratic ease-out; the angle increases linearly. The result is a smooth spiral, tightening as it reaches the center.

---

## Easing a Radial Expand (Ease-Out from Center)

Three boxes easing outward from a shared center, each along a different radial line:

```scheme
(let ((center-x 300)
      (center-y 300)
      (box1 (world/spawn 'box :x center-x :y center-y :color 'red))
      (box2 (world/spawn 'box :x center-x :y center-y :color 'green))
      (box3 (world/spawn 'box :x center-x :y center-y :color 'blue)))
  (entity/glide! box1 (+ center-x 120) center-y :frames 60 :ease 'out)
  (entity/glide! box2 (+ center-x (* 120 (dcos (* PI 0.666))))
                       (+ center-y (* 120 (dsin (* PI 0.666))))
                       :frames 60 :ease 'out)
  (entity/glide! box3 (+ center-x (* 120 (dcos (* PI 1.333))))
                       (+ center-y (* 120 (dsin (* PI 1.333))))
                       :frames 60 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 60))
```

All three ease outward at the same rate. The formation expands smoothly, like a flower opening.

---

## Easing a Radial Collapse (Ease-In to Center)

The reverse: three boxes easing inward from different positions to a shared center:

```scheme
(let ((center-x 300)
      (center-y 300)
      (box1 (world/spawn 'box :x 450 :y 300 :color 'red))
      (box2 (world/spawn 'box :x 250 :y 450 :color 'green))
      (box3 (world/spawn 'box :x 250 :y 150 :color 'blue)))
  (entity/glide! box1 center-x center-y :frames 60 :ease 'in)
  (entity/glide! box2 center-x center-y :frames 60 :ease 'in)
  (entity/glide! box3 center-x center-y :frames 60 :ease 'in)
  (world/step 60))
```

All three accelerate inward and arrive together. Same easing, different starting positions.

---

## Easing with a Pause Before Each Move

A box making a three-leg journey, pausing 20 frames before each move:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)))
  (world/step 20)
  (entity/glide! box 200 150 :frames 40 :ease 'in-out)
  (world/step 40)
  (world/step 20)
  (entity/glide! box 350 300 :frames 40 :ease 'in-out)
  (world/step 40)
  (world/step 20)
  (entity/glide! box 500 150 :frames 40 :ease 'in-out)
  (world/step 40))
```

The pauses give the sequence a *deliberate* rhythm. The easing gives each move weight. Together, they create a sense of *thought* — the box is deciding where to go next.

---

## Easing a Fade-In While Moving

A box that starts invisible and fades in while gliding, both eased:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300 :alpha 0.0)))
  (entity/set! box 'alpha-target 1.0)
  (entity/set! box 'alpha-frames 60)
  (entity/set! box 'alpha-ease 'out)
  (entity/glide! box 350 300 :frames 60 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 60))
```

<!-- BUILD: entity alpha tweening placeholder -->
*[needs: entity alpha interpolation]*

Both properties ease out simultaneously. The box *arrives* visually and spatially at the same moment. This is compound easing — multiple properties eased in parallel.

---

## Easing a Rotation While Gliding

A box gliding and rotating simultaneously, both eased in-out:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300 :angle 0)))
  (entity/set! box 'angle-target PI)
  (entity/set! box 'angle-frames 60)
  (entity/set! box 'angle-ease 'in-out)
  (entity/glide! box 350 300 :frames 60 :ease 'in-out)
  (world/step 60))
```

<!-- BUILD: entity angle tweening placeholder -->
*[needs: entity angle interpolation]*

The glide and spin share the same duration and easing. The motion feels *unified* — the rotation isn't an afterthought, it's part of the same gesture.

---

## Easing a Scale Change (Growing/Shrinking)

A box that grows while gliding, both eased:

```scheme
(let ((box (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300 :scale 0.5)))
  (entity/set! box 'scale-target 2.0)
  (entity/set! box 'scale-frames 60)
  (entity/set! box 'scale-ease 'out)
  (entity/glide! box 350 300 :frames 60 :ease 'out)
  (world/step 60))
```

<!-- BUILD: entity scale tweening placeholder -->
*[needs: entity scale interpolation]*

The box arrives *and* reaches full size at the same moment. Growth is eased just like position. The principle extends to any interpolatable property.

---

## Easing a Chain of Linked Entities

Two boxes, the second following the first with a delay, both easing toward the same destination:

```scheme
(let ((leader (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 250 :color 'red))
      (follower (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300 :color 'blue)))
  (entity/glide! leader 350 250 :frames 60 :ease 'in-out)
  (world/step 15)
  (entity/glide! follower 350 300 :frames 60 :ease 'in-out)
  (world/step 60))
```

The 15-frame delay gives the follower a *trailing* quality. Both ease the same way, but the offset makes it feel like the follower is *chasing*, not just moving in parallel.

---

## Easing a Flock (Many Entities, Staggered Start)

Five boxes gliding to the same destination, each starting a few frames after the last:

```scheme
(let ((boxes (list (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 150)
                   (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 200)
                   (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 250)
                   (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 300)
                   (world/spawn 'box :x 50 :y 350))))
  (letrec ((launch (lambda (bs delay)
                     (when (not (null? bs))
                       (entity/glide! (car bs) 400 (entity/y (car bs)) :frames 60 :ease 'out)
                       (world/step delay)
                       (launch (cdr bs) delay)))))
    (launch boxes 8)
    (world/step 60)))
```

The stagger creates a *wave* — the boxes don't all move at once, they *flow*. Same easing, same duration, different start times.

---

## Exercises

1. **The Gentle Door**: A door sprite at `x: 300, y: 300, angle: 0` swings open (rotating to `angle: PI/2`) over 50 frames with ease-out, holds open for 40 frames, then swings shut (back to `angle: 0`) over 50 frames with ease-in. The swing should feel *weighted* — slow to start, settling gently.

2. **The Settling Leaf**: A leaf at `x: 300, y: 50` falls to `y: 500` over 120 frames, but with a custom easing: ease-in for the first third (accelerating under gravity), linear for the middle third (terminal velocity), and elastic-out for the last third (tumbling to rest). Each phase should be a separate glide.

3. **The Spiral Departure**: A box at `x: 300, y: 300` spirals outward along a circular path, the radius growing from 0 to 200 over 100 frames with ease-in, while the angle increases linearly (completing 3 full rotations). The motion should feel like a spring unwinding.

4. **The Accordion Formation**: Four boxes in a horizontal line at `y: 300`, starting at `x: 100, 200, 300, 400`. They collapse inward to a shared center at `x: 250` with ease-in over 40 frames, hold for 20 frames, then expand back to their original positions with ease-out over 40 frames. The formation should *breathe*.

5. **The Attention Pulse**: A box at `x: 300, y: 300, scale: 1.0` grows to `scale: 1.3` over 20 frames with ease-out, shrinks back to `scale: 1.0` over 20 frames with ease-in, and repeats this cycle 3 times. The pulse should feel *alive*, like the box is breathing or calling for attention.

6. **The Chase with Variable Easing**: A red box (leader) glides from `x: 50, y: 300` to `x: 500, y: 300` over 80 frames with ease-in-out. A blue box (chaser) starts at `x: 50, y: 350` and glides to the *current position* of the leader (sampled at frame 40) over 60 frames with ease-out, starting at frame 20. The chaser should arrive smoothly but not catch the leader.


---

## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### Linear motion (no easing)

Before we curve time, let's see what we're leaving behind. A circle crosses the canvas at constant speed—every frame covers the same distance.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.0)
         (progress (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (x (+ 50 (* progress 700))))
    (fill 100 150 250)
    (circle x 300 30)))
```

[VISUAL: A blue circle sliding left-to-right at unwavering speed, looping.]

The motion is *correct* but lifeless. No anticipation, no arrival—just traverse.

---


### Ease-out: the settling stone

A stone tossed onto ice: fast at first, friction slowing it down, rolling to rest. We'll square the progress to front-load the distance.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600))))
    (fill 180 100 80)
    (circle x 280 28)))
```

[VISUAL: An orange circle bursts across the left half, then decelerates smoothly to rest on the right.]

The squared falloff—`(- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))`—spends most of the motion near the end position. The arrival feels *intentional*.

---


### Ease-in: the winding pitch

A pitcher's arm: slow pullback, explosive release. Distance accumulates toward the end.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 1.8)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (* t t))
         (y (+ 100 (* eased 400))))
    (fill 250 200 100)
    (circle 400 y 25)))
```

[VISUAL: A yellow circle creeps downward, then accelerates sharply toward the bottom.]

Squaring `t` directly creates the opposite shape: crawl, then rush.

---


### Ease-in-out: the breath

A breath in, a breath out—smooth at the start, smooth at the end, fastest in the middle. We'll blend ease-in and ease-out.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 3.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (if (< t 0.5)
                    (* 2 t t)
                    (- 1 (* 2 (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600))))
    (fill 150 250 200)
    (circle x 350 26)))
```

[VISUAL: A mint-green circle eases away from the left edge, speeds through the center, eases to rest on the right.]

The `if` switches from ease-in (first half) to ease-out (second half). The motion feels *considered* at both ends.

---


### Cubic ease-out: the weighted settle

Squaring gives a gentle curve. Cubing it—`(- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))`—creates a sharper start and a longer tail, like a heavy bag swinging to rest.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.2)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (x (+ 80 (* eased 640))))
    (fill 200 120 180)
    (circle x 420 32)))
```

[VISUAL: A mauve circle rockets partway, then glides to a gentle stop.]

More \"weight\" in the deceleration—useful for something that has inertia.

---


### Cubic ease-in: the slingshot

Cubing `t` directly: almost no movement at first, then a sharp ramp.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 1.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (* t t t))
         (y (+ 120 (* eased 360))))
    (fill 100 200 250)
    (circle 300 y 24)))
```

[VISUAL: A cyan circle hangs near the top, then drops rapidly.]

The long pause at the start can feel like winding a spring.

---


### Quartic ease-in-out: the sigh

Fourth power—`t^4`—creates an even gentler start and stop, with a faster middle. A slow sigh.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 4.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (if (< t 0.5)
                    (* 8 t t t t)
                    (- 1 (* 8 (- 1 t) (- 1 t) (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
         (scale (+ 0.3 (* eased 0.7))))
    (fill 255 220 150)
    (circle 400 300 (* scale 80))))
```

[VISUAL: A pale-yellow circle grows from small to large, lingering at both extremes.]

The motion feels *luxurious*—no hurry.

---


### Ease-out on vertical drop

A ball tossed upward, falling back down—gravity gives a natural ease-in to the peak, ease-out on the descent.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (y (- 500 (* eased 300))))
    (fill 250 100 100)
    (circle 500 y 28)))
```

[VISUAL: A red circle starts low, decelerates upward, then loops.]

Flipping the y direction with `(- 500 ...)` makes it rise instead of fall.

---


### Sine ease-in-out: the smoothest blend

Sine and cosine can shape an ease that has no visible \"joint\" between the two halves—perfectly smooth acceleration into deceleration.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 3.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (* 0.5 (- 1 (cos (* t 3.14159)))))
         (x (+ 60 (* eased 680))))
    (fill 180 160 250)
    (circle x 220 30)))
```

[VISUAL: A lavender circle glides with a perfectly smooth S-curve.]

`(cos (* t pi))` swings from 1 to -1; scaling and offsetting maps it to 0→1. The curve is *continuous* in both value and slope.

---


### Ease-out rotation

A dial turning to a setting—fast at first, slowing as it nears the mark.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (angle (* eased 6.28)))
    (push-matrix)
    (translate 400 300)
    (rotate angle)
    (fill 100 250 150)
    (rect -50 -10 100 20)
    (pop-matrix)))
```

[VISUAL: A green bar rotates from horizontal, slowing as it completes a full turn.]

The same quadratic ease-out, applied to angle instead of position.

---


### Elastic ease-out: the spring

A real spring overshoots and wobbles back. We'll mimic that with a decaying sine wave.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (decay (expt 2 (* -10 t)))
         (wave (sin (* t 7 3.14159)))
         (eased (+ 1 (* decay wave)))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600))))
    (fill 250 180 100)
    (circle x 380 26)))
```

[VISUAL: An orange circle rockets past the right edge, bounces back, settles with shrinking wobbles.]

`(expt 2 (* -10 t))` is exponential decay; multiplying it by `(sin ...)` creates the damped oscillation.

---


### Ease-in with anticipation

Before a character jumps forward, they crouch back—a tiny reverse motion that *loads* the jump.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 1.2)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (anticipation (if (< t 0.15)
                           (* -0.5 (/ t 0.15))
                           0))
         (eased (* (max 0 (- t 0.15)) (max 0 (- t 0.15))))
         (total (+ anticipation eased))
         (x (+ 200 (* total 400))))
    (fill 100 200 250)
    (circle x 320 30)))
```

[VISUAL: A cyan circle nudges left, then accelerates hard to the right.]

The first 15% of the motion runs *backward*; the rest is a standard ease-in. The pullback makes the launch feel stronger.

---


### Ease-out with overshoot

After arriving, the object drifts a bit past the target, then settles back—common in UI animation.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 1.8)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (base (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (overshoot (if (> base 0.95)
                        (* 0.08 (sin (* (- base 0.95) 31.4)))
                        0))
         (eased (+ base overshoot))
         (y (+ 150 (* eased 300))))
    (fill 250 200 150)
    (circle 350 y 28)))
```

[VISUAL: A peach circle drops, settles just below the target, bounces up slightly, then rests.]

The sine wave kicks in only after 95% progress, adding a small wiggle.

---


### Back ease-in: the windup

Before moving forward, the motion pulls *past zero* in the opposite direction—like drawing a bow.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 1.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (c 1.70158)
         (eased (* t t (- (* (+ c 1) t) c)))
         (x (+ 400 (* eased 300))))
    (fill 200 100 250)
    (circle x 260 25)))
```

[VISUAL: A purple circle drifts left (below x=400), then accelerates sharply right.]

The magic constant `1.70158` is tuned to produce a visible but not extreme pullback.

---


### Back ease-out: the settle

The mirror of back-ease-in: the motion overshoots the target, then pulls back to rest.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 1.8)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (c 1.70158)
         (t1 (- t 1))
         (eased (+ 1 (* t1 t1 (+ (* (+ c 1) t1) c))))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600))))
    (fill 100 250 200)
    (circle x 340 27)))
```

[VISUAL: A teal circle rushes past the right edge, then pulls back gently to rest.]

Same constant, rearranged for ease-out.

---


### Bounce ease-out: the basketball

A ball dropped on pavement—each bounce smaller than the last.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (cond
                  ((< t (/ 1 2.75)) (* 7.5625 t t))
                  ((< t (/ 2 2.75)) (let ((t2 (- t (/ 1.5 2.75))))
                                      (+ 0.75 (* 7.5625 t2 t2))))
                  ((< t (/ 2.5 2.75)) (let ((t2 (- t (/ 2.25 2.75))))
                                        (+ 0.9375 (* 7.5625 t2 t2))))
                  (else (let ((t2 (- t (/ 2.625 2.75))))
                          (+ 0.984375 (* 7.5625 t2 t2))))))
         (y (- 500 (* eased 350))))
    (fill 250 140 80)
    (circle 450 y 30)))
```

[VISUAL: An orange circle falls, bounces high, bounces medium, bounces small, settles.]

Four parabolic arcs of decreasing height, stitched together with `cond`.

---


### Exponential ease-out: the car brake

Exponential decay—like friction or air resistance slowing a moving object.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (expt 2 (* -10 t))))
         (x (+ 80 (* eased 640))))
    (fill 250 100 150)
    (circle x 280 28)))
```

[VISUAL: A pink circle decelerates with a long, smooth tail—always slowing, never quite stopping.]

`(expt 2 (* -10 t))` drops from 1 toward 0, asymptotically.

---


### Exponential ease-in: the rocket ignition

The inverse: exponential *growth*—slow, slow, then sudden explosion.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 1.6)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (expt 2 (* 10 (- t 1))))
         (y (+ 100 (* eased 400))))
    (fill 255 200 100)
    (circle 500 y 26)))
```

[VISUAL: A yellow circle hangs near the top, then rockets downward.]

Barely moves for most of the duration, then *launches*.

---


### Circular ease-in-out: arc-based smoothness

Instead of polynomial or exponential, we carve the ease from a circular arc—sqrt-based falloff.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 3.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (if (< t 0.5)
                    (* 0.5 (- 1 (sqrt (- 1 (* 4 t t)))))
                    (* 0.5 (+ 1 (sqrt (- 1 (* (- (* 2 t) 2)
                                              (- (* 2 t) 2))))))))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600))))
    (fill 180 220 250)
    (circle x 360 29)))
```

[VISUAL: A light-blue circle eases with a subtly different curve—gentler than quadratic, sharper than sine.]

The sqrt creates a different \"feel\"—worth having in the toolkit.

---


### Ease applied to opacity

Easing isn't just spatial—it shapes any parameter. A circle fades in with ease-out, making the appearance feel soft.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (alpha (* eased 255)))
    (fill 100 250 150 alpha)
    (circle 400 300 60)))
```

[VISUAL: A green circle materializes, opacity rising quickly at first, then leveling off.]

Same quadratic ease-out, applied to the alpha channel.

---


### Ease applied to scale

A circle grows into view—ease-in-out so it doesn't pop or freeze, just *arrives*.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (if (< t 0.5)
                    (* 2 t t)
                    (- 1 (* 2 (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
         (radius (* eased 70)))
    (fill 250 180 200)
    (circle 400 300 radius)))
```

[VISUAL: A pink circle grows from a dot to full size, easing at both ends.]

Scale is a natural home for ease-in-out—avoids the \"pop\" of instant appearance.

---


### Ease applied to hue

Color can ease, too. A circle shifts from blue to orange over time.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 4.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (* 0.5 (- 1 (cos (* t 3.14159)))))
         (hue-start 210)
         (hue-end 30)
         (hue (+ hue-start (* eased (- hue-end hue-start)))))
    (colorMode 'HSB 360 100 100)
    (fill hue 80 90)
    (circle 400 300 70)
    (colorMode 'RGB 255 255 255)))
```

[VISUAL: A large circle smoothly shifts from blue through purple to orange.]

*[needs: colorMode/HSB support]*  
The sine ease makes the hue transition feel natural, not linear.

---


### Staggered ease: three circles

Three circles, each starting their ease-out motion at a different time—creates a wave.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let ((duration 2.0))
    (define (draw-circle delay y-pos hue)
      (let* ((t (max 0 (- (mod (world-time) (+ duration delay)) delay)))
             (progress (min 1 (/ t duration)))
             (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 progress) (- 1 progress))))
             (x (+ 100 (* eased 600))))
        (fill hue 100 200)
        (circle x y-pos 24)))
    (draw-circle 0.0 250 250)
    (draw-circle 0.3 320 180)
    (draw-circle 0.6 390 100)))
```

[VISUAL: Three circles—red, orange, green—slide right in sequence, each easing out.]

The wave effect comes from offset start times.

---


### Ease with clamped range

Sometimes we only want easing over part of the motion—first half eases, second half is linear.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (ease-duration 0.4)
         (eased (if (< t ease-duration)
                    (- 1 (* (- 1 (/ t ease-duration))
                            (- 1 (/ t ease-duration))))
                    1))
         (x (+ 100 (* t 600)))
         (y (+ 200 (* eased 200))))
    (fill 100 200 250)
    (circle x y 26)))
```

[VISUAL: A cyan circle moves diagonally—vertical motion eases out in the first 40%, then stops; horizontal motion continues linearly.]

Useful when one dimension settles while another keeps moving.

---


### Ease reversal: ping-pong

A circle eases out to the right, then eases back to the left—like a pendulum with no swing-through.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((half-duration 1.5)
         (full-duration (* 2 half-duration))
         (raw-t (mod (world-time) full-duration))
         (t (if (< raw-t half-duration)
                (/ raw-t half-duration)
                (- 1 (/ (- raw-t half-duration) half-duration))))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (x (+ 150 (* eased 500))))
    (fill 250 200 100)
    (circle x 300 30)))
```

[VISUAL: A yellow circle eases right, pauses, eases left, pauses, repeats.]

The `if` flips `t` after the halfway point, creating symmetry.

---


### Ease combining two properties

A circle moves horizontally with ease-out, grows vertically with ease-in—different curves, same timeline.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (ease-out (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (ease-in (* t t))
         (x (+ 100 (* ease-out 600)))
         (height (+ 20 (* ease-in 100))))
    (fill 180 100 250)
    (ellipse x 300 40 height)))
```

[VISUAL: A purple ellipse slides right (easing out) while stretching tall (easing in).]

Different eases on different properties—common in real animation.

---


### Multi-segment ease: three-part journey

A circle eases in for 1 second, moves linearly for 1 second, eases out for 1 second.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((t (mod (world-time) 3.0))
         (eased (cond
                  ((< t 1.0) (* (/ t 1.0) (/ t 1.0) 0.333))
                  ((< t 2.0) (+ 0.333 (* (- t 1.0) 0.333)))
                  (else (let ((t2 (/ (- t 2.0) 1.0)))
                          (+ 0.666 (* (- 1 (* (- 1 t2) (- 1 t2))) 0.333))))))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600))))
    (fill 100 250 200)
    (circle x 350 28)))
```

[VISUAL: A teal circle creeps forward, glides at constant speed, then settles gently.]

Three distinct phases, stitched by hand.

---


### Ease with noise modulation

Ease-out provides the overall arc; a little noise adds organic jitter.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (jitter (* 8 (sin (* (world-time) 23.7))))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600)))
         (y (+ 300 jitter)))
    (fill 250 150 100)
    (circle x y 26)))
```

[VISUAL: An orange circle eases right along a gently wobbling path.]

The jitter doesn't interfere with the ease—it's a separate, small offset.

---


### Ease delayed start

A circle waits 1 second, then eases in. The delay creates anticipation.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((delay 1.0)
         (duration 1.5)
         (elapsed (mod (world-time) (+ delay duration)))
         (t (max 0 (/ (- elapsed delay) duration)))
         (eased (* t t))
         (y (+ 150 (* eased 350))))
    (fill 250 100 180)
    (circle 400 y 28)))
```

[VISUAL: A pink circle sits still at the top, then accelerates downward.]

The `max` clamps t to zero during the delay.

---


### Ease on rotation with multiple cycles

A dial spins 3 full rotations, easing in and out over the entire journey.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 4.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (if (< t 0.5)
                    (* 2 t t)
                    (- 1 (* 2 (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
         (angle (* eased 3 6.28318)))
    (push-matrix)
    (translate 400 300)
    (rotate angle)
    (fill 100 200 250)
    (rect -60 -12 120 24)
    (pop-matrix)))
```

[VISUAL: A cyan bar eases into a triple spin, then eases to rest.]

Multiplying by 3 gives three full rotations; the ease shapes the entire multi-turn journey.

---


### Vertical ease with gravity feel

A box rises with ease-out (like thrown upward), implying deceleration against gravity.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 1.8)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (y (- 450 (* eased 300))))
    (fill 100 250 150)
    (rect 360 y 80 40)))
```

[VISUAL: A green rectangle launches upward, slowing as it climbs.]

The same quadratic ease-out, but the reversed y direction mimics a toss.

---


### Ease with non-zero start and end

A slider moves from 30% to 80% of the canvas width, easing in-out over that range.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (if (< t 0.5)
                    (* 2 t t)
                    (- 1 (* 2 (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
         (start-x 240)
         (end-x 640)
         (x (+ start-x (* eased (- end-x start-x)))))
    (fill 200 100 250)
    (circle x 320 26)))
```

[VISUAL: A purple circle eases from 30% to 80% of the width, not starting at the left edge.]

Easing works over any range—just interpolate between start and end values.

---


### Ease with conditional reversal

If the mouse is on the left half of the screen, ease right; if on the right half, ease left.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (target (if (< (mouse-x) 400) 600 200))
         (x (+ 400 (* (- target 400) eased))))
    (fill 250 200 150)
    (circle x 300 30)))
```

[VISUAL: A peach circle eases toward the right or left edge depending on mouse position.]

*[needs: mouse-x support]*  
The ease shape stays the same; only the target changes.

---


### Ease applied to stroke weight

A circle's outline thickens with ease-in-out, while the circle itself stays still.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 3.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (if (< t 0.5)
                    (* 2 t t)
                    (- 1 (* 2 (- 1 t) (- 1 t)))))
         (weight (+ 2 (* eased 18))))
    (no-fill)
    (stroke 100 200 250)
    (stroke-weight weight)
    (circle 400 300 100)))
```

[VISUAL: A cyan outline circle pulses from thin to thick and back.]

*[needs: no-fill, stroke, stroke-weight support]*  
Any numeric property can be eased.

---


### Ease interpolating between two circles

Two circles sit at opposite corners. A third circle eases between them, both in position and color.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 3.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (* 0.5 (- 1 (cos (* t 3.14159)))))
         (x (+ 150 (* eased 500)))
         (y (+ 200 (* eased 200)))
         (r (+ 100 (* eased 150)))
         (g (+ 250 (* eased -150)))
         (b 200))
    (fill r g b)
    (circle x y 35)))
```

[VISUAL: A circle glides diagonally from top-left to bottom-right, shifting from cyan to orange.]

Sine ease-in-out on position *and* color—smooth on all axes.

---


### Ease with time-scaled loop

A circle completes its ease-out in 1 second, then pauses for 2 seconds before restarting.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((active 1.0)
         (pause 2.0)
         (total (+ active pause))
         (cycle-t (mod (world-time) total))
         (t (min 1 (/ cycle-t active)))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600))))
    (fill 250 220 100)
    (circle x 280 28)))
```

[VISUAL: A yellow circle eases right, then holds position for 2 seconds, then resets.]

The `min` clamps progress at 1 once the active phase ends.

---


### Ease with asymmetric in/out

Ease in over 30% of the duration, ease out over 70%—different speeds for different halves.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (if (< t 0.3)
                    (* (/ t 0.3) (/ t 0.3) 0.5)
                    (+ 0.5 (* (- 1 (* (- 1 (/ (- t 0.3) 0.7))
                                      (- 1 (/ (- t 0.3) 0.7))))
                              0.5))))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600))))
    (fill 180 250 200)
    (circle x 340 30)))
```

[VISUAL: A mint circle accelerates sharply in the first third, then glides gently to rest.]

Asymmetry gives the motion a lopsided, naturalistic feel.

---


### Ease with parameter remapping

Instead of 0→1, we ease from 0→0.6, creating a partial journey.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (partial (* eased 0.6))
         (x (+ 150 (* partial 500))))
    (fill 250 150 200)
    (circle x 300 28)))
```

[VISUAL: A pink circle eases 60% of the way across, never reaching the far edge.]

Useful when motion is interrupted or intentionally incomplete.

---


### Ease-out with floor collision

A circle falls with ease-in (gravity), then stops abruptly when it hits y=500—no ease on the stop.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 1.5)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (* t t))
         (y-target (+ 100 (* eased 400)))
         (y (min y-target 500)))
    (fill 250 100 100)
    (circle 400 y 32)))
```

[VISUAL: A red circle accelerates downward, then stops hard at the bottom.]

The `min` creates an artificial floor—no bounce, just a sudden stop. The contrast with easing shows the difference.

---


### Ease combined with sine oscillation

A circle eases right while bobbing up and down—two independent motions, one eased, one periodic.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 3.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600)))
         (y-bob (* 30 (sin (* (world-time) 4))))
         (y (+ 300 y-bob)))
    (fill 100 250 200)
    (circle x y 28)))
```

[VISUAL: A teal circle eases right along a gently waving vertical path.]

The horizontal ease and the vertical sine don't interfere—they're orthogonal.

---


### Cubic ease-in-out

Cubic power (t³) for both halves—a sharper ease than quadratic, but not as extreme as quartic.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.8)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (eased (if (< t 0.5)
                    (* 4 t t t)
                    (+ 1 (* 4 (- t 1) (- t 1) (- t 1)))))
         (x (+ 100 (* eased 600))))
    (fill 200 180 250)
    (circle x 360 30)))
```

[VISUAL: A lavender circle eases with a pronounced S-curve—slow, fast, slow.]

Cubic is a sweet spot—more character than quadratic, less languid than quartic.

---


### Ease-out with early cutoff

The ease runs for 70% of the duration, then the object holds position.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 2.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (active-t (min (/ t 0.7) 1.0))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 active-t) (- 1 active-t))))
         (x (+ 120 (* eased 560))))
    (fill 100 200 250)
    (circle x 320 28)))
```

[VISUAL: A cyan circle eases 70% of the way in 70% of the time, then freezes.]

Useful for \"settle and wait\" behaviors.

---


### Ease on arc radius

A circle travels in a circular path—easing the *radius* makes it spiral outward.

```scheme
(define (render)
  (let* ((duration 4.0)
         (t (/ (mod (world-time) duration) duration))
         (angle (* t 6.28318 2))
         (eased (- 1 (* (- 1 t) (- 1 t))))
         (radius (* eased 150))
         (x (+ 400 (* radius (cos angle))))
         (y (+ 300 (* radius (sin angle)))))
    (fill 250 180 120)
    (circle x y 24)))
```

[VISUAL: A peach circle spirals outward over two full rotations, easing from center to edge.]

The radius ease and the angular sweep combine into a smooth spiral.

